==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ode
<hw>Ode</hw> <pr>(⟦omac⟧d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>ode</ets>, <ets>oda</ets>, Gr. <grk>'w,dh`</grk> a song, especially
a lyric song, contr. fr. <grk>'aoidh`</grk>, fr. <grk>'aei`dein</grk> to
sing; cf. Skr. <ets>vad</ets> to speak, sing. Cf. <er>Comedy</er>,
<er>Melody</er>, <er>Monody</er>.]</ety> <def>A short poetical
composition proper to be set to music or sung; a lyric poem; esp., now,
a poem characterized by sustained noble sentiment and appropriate
dignity of style.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hangs <qex>odes</qex> upon hawthorns and elegies on brambles.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O! run; prevent them with thy humble <qex>ode</qex>,⟦br⟧
And lay it lowly at his blessed feet.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Ode factor</b></col>, <cd>one who makes, or who traffics
in, odes; -- used contemptuously.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Odelet</ent>⟦br⟧
